{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507661"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:55:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:55:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2656"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2656"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.02,0.17,0.62,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2656"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39795"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2656"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2656"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24299"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"766"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3115"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39795"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents with a three month history of intermittent dull left sided abdominal pain. The pain appears to be worse after meals and then gradually settles, particularly once she has had a bowel action. She has had similar symptoms for several years, but thinks they are now more noticeable. She has no other gastrointestinal symptoms and is otherwise in good health, with no previous illnesses of any significance. On examination her blood pressure is 130/90 mmHg, pulse 80/min and temperature 37.2C. Examination of her abdomen is unremarkable. A CT scan is arranged (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is shown on the scan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Adrenal neoplasm","Splenomegaly","Situs inversus","Left renal neoplasm"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms are probably due to no more than irritable bowel syndrome. With this clinical picture, it is questionable why a CT scan was performed. However, the reality is that CT scans are being performed with increasing frequency, often for dubious clinical reasons. In this case the CT shows a mass in the left upper quadrant. Taken together with the dextrocardia, this patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Esitus inversus\u003C/strong\u003E. There are no other abnormal findings on the CT, but if this was not situs inversus, thought could be given to a (very) large \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal neoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenomegaly\u003C/strong\u003E, a \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrointestinal stromal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E or possibly a \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal neoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Incidental findings are frequently detected in abdominal CT scans."],"references":["Umar UKA, Alremeithi AN, Qayyum H. Incidental diagnosis of situs inversus totalis: a perspective from an emergency department attendance. BMJ Case Reports. 2021; 14(4)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24299"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2656"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16884"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16884"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/59bdb76d-4f7a-4166-810b-e3f610adda18.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.eme